{"title":"Ridley Falcn RS merges aero and lightweight to take on Tarmac SL8","link":"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/news/ridley-falcn-rs","date":1694160000000,"content":"<p><a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk\">Cyclist</a><br />\n<a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/news/ridley-falcn-rs\">Ridley Falcn RS merges aero and lightweight to take on Tarmac SL8</a></p>\n\n<p>The new Ridley Falcn RS is a lightweight-slash-aero race bike, which the brand says is as aerodynamic as its <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/reviews/ridley-noah-fast-disc-review\" target=\"_blank\">Noah Fast</a> and almost as light as the <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/reviews/ridley-helium-slx-disc-review\" target=\"_blank\">Helium SLX</a>. The Falcn RS is available in three specs at launch with UK prices of £8,599 with <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/reviews/sram-force-etap-axs-groupset-review\" target=\"_blank\">SRAM Force AXS</a> or <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/reviews/shimano-dura-ace-r9200-and-ultegra-r8100-shimano-finally-goes-12-speed\" target=\"_blank\">Shimano Ultegra</a> or £6,799 with <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/news/shimano-105-di2\" target=\"_blank\">Shimano 105 Di2</a>.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Ridley labels the new Falcn RS as ‘the ultimate all-round performance road bike’ and says that it is highly aerodynamically efficient, lightweight, stiff and ready for any kind of road racing. As with any newer bike model, there’s room for wider tyres, in this case 34mm, with the Falcn optimised for 28mm rubber.</p>\n\n\n\n<h2>Aero and lightweight</h2>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"970\" height=\"647\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/Falcn_RS_01-CopyrightRidley-5-970x647.jpg\" alt=\"Cornering on a mountain road\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/Falcn_RS_01-CopyrightRidley-5-970x646.jpg 970w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/Falcn_RS_01-CopyrightRidley-5-300x200.jpg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/Falcn_RS_01-CopyrightRidley-5-768x512.jpg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/Falcn_RS_01-CopyrightRidley-5-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/Falcn_RS_01-CopyrightRidley-5-2048x1365.jpg 2048w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/Falcn_RS_01-CopyrightRidley-5-750x500.jpg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/Falcn_RS_01-CopyrightRidley-5-1140x760.jpg 1140w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/Falcn_RS_01-CopyrightRidley-5-465x310.jpg 465w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/Falcn_RS_01-CopyrightRidley-5-620x413.jpg 620w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/Falcn_RS_01-CopyrightRidley-5-350x233.jpg 350w\" /><figcaption>Ridley</figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>Ridley suggests that rather than stiffness-to-weight (aren’t all new bikes X per cent stiffer than their predecessor?), the focus of performance bike design has shifted to aero-to-weight. </p>\n\n\n\n<p>The brand says the new Falcn RS is as aero as the <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/reviews/ridley-noah-fast-disc-review\" target=\"_blank\">Noah Fast</a> aero bike, but just 110g heavier than the non-aero, round-tubed <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/reviews/ridley-helium-slx-disc-review\" target=\"_blank\">Helium SLX</a> climbing bike. It claims a frame weight of 825g for a size medium bike, with an additional 380g for the fork.</p>\n\n\n<div>\r\n                <div>\r\n                   <div>\r\n                      <div>\r\n                         <h4><span>Related Posts</span></h4>\r\n                      </div>\r\n                      <div>\r\n                         <div>\r\n                            <div>\r\n                            <article>\r\n                    <div>\r\n                       <h4>\r\n                          <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/uphill-battle-aero-vs-lightweight-field-test\">Aero vs. lightweight bike: Which is better for climbing?</a>\r\n                       </h4>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                 </article><article>\r\n                    <div>\r\n                       <h4>\r\n                          <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/how-to-win-against-the-wind\">How to get more aero on your bike</a>\r\n                       </h4>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                 </article><article>\r\n                    <div>\r\n                       <h4>\r\n                          <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/buying-guides/best-aero-bikes\">Best aero bikes 2023: Ride faster for less effort</a>\r\n                       </h4>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                 </article><article>\r\n                    <div>\r\n                       <h4>\r\n                          <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/cycling-science-is-it-worth-drafting-uphill\">Cycling science: Is it worth drafting uphill?</a>\r\n                       </h4>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                 </article></div>\r\n                                    </div>\r\n                                    <div>\r\n                                    <div>\r\n                                        <div>\r\n                                            <span></span><span></span><span></span>\r\n                                        </div>\r\n                                        <div>\r\n                                            <div>\r\n                                                <div></div>\r\n                                            </div>\r\n                                        </div>\r\n                                        <div>\r\n                                            <div>\r\n                                                <div></div>\r\n                                            </div>\r\n                                        </div>\r\n                                    </div>\r\n                                    </div>\r\n                                </div>\r\n                                <div>\r\n                                    <div>\r\n                                    <div>\r\n                                        <span></span>\r\n                                        <span></span>\r\n                                        <span></span>\r\n                                    </div>\r\n                                    </div>\r\n                                </div>\r\n                                \r\n                            </div>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                        </div>\n\n\n<p>Ridley also stresses that aerodynamics are important even when riding uphill, so that the Falcn RS is faster than the Helium SLX on climbs even though it carries the small additional weight.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>As with many new bike designs, the Falcn RS has a deeper head tube and aero optimised tube profiles. Ridley says that the top tube has been shaped to enhance the bike’s <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/tutorials/how-to-ride-in-crosswinds\" target=\"_blank\">crosswind stability</a>. At the rear, Ridley has aimed to reduce weight in the seat tube and seatstays. </p>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"970\" height=\"647\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/FalcnRS_Packshots-CopyrightRidley-5-970x647.jpg\" alt srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/FalcnRS_Packshots-CopyrightRidley-5-970x646.jpg 970w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/FalcnRS_Packshots-CopyrightRidley-5-300x200.jpg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/FalcnRS_Packshots-CopyrightRidley-5-768x512.jpg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/FalcnRS_Packshots-CopyrightRidley-5-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/FalcnRS_Packshots-CopyrightRidley-5-2048x1366.jpg 2048w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/FalcnRS_Packshots-CopyrightRidley-5-750x500.jpg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/FalcnRS_Packshots-CopyrightRidley-5-1140x760.jpg 1140w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/FalcnRS_Packshots-CopyrightRidley-5-465x310.jpg 465w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/FalcnRS_Packshots-CopyrightRidley-5-620x413.jpg 620w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/FalcnRS_Packshots-CopyrightRidley-5-350x233.jpg 350w\" /><figcaption>Ridley </figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>Another aero feature that Ridley emphasises is the aero diffuser built into the fork crown. It says that this develops turbulence in the airflow ahead of the down tube, which results in improved airflow and a claimed 10 per cent reduction in drag at 50kmh relative to a non-diffuser fork.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Diffusers are a feature built into Formula 1 cars and a fork crown diffuser is a feature also included in the recently launched BMC Speedmachine time-trial/triathlon bike. </p>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"970\" height=\"647\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/Falcn_RS_01-CopyrightRidley-21-970x647.jpg\" alt=\"Riding fast on the flat\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/Falcn_RS_01-CopyrightRidley-21-970x646.jpg 970w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/Falcn_RS_01-CopyrightRidley-21-300x200.jpg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/Falcn_RS_01-CopyrightRidley-21-768x512.jpg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/Falcn_RS_01-CopyrightRidley-21-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/Falcn_RS_01-CopyrightRidley-21-2048x1365.jpg 2048w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/Falcn_RS_01-CopyrightRidley-21-750x500.jpg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/Falcn_RS_01-CopyrightRidley-21-1140x760.jpg 1140w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/Falcn_RS_01-CopyrightRidley-21-465x310.jpg 465w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/Falcn_RS_01-CopyrightRidley-21-620x413.jpg 620w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/Falcn_RS_01-CopyrightRidley-21-350x233.jpg 350w\" /><figcaption>Ridley</figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>Ridley’s aero/lightweight approach has much in common with Specialized’s new <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/news/specialized-tarmac-sl8-news\" target=\"_blank\">Tarmac SL8</a>, which is designed to be more aero while hitting the UCI’s 6.8kg weight limit, with Specialized saying that the new Tarmac is 16 seconds <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/specialized-tarmac-sl8-vs-sl7\" target=\"_blank\">faster than the older Tarmac SL7</a> over the<a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/classic-tour-de-france-climbs-col-du-tourmalet\" target=\"_blank\"> Col du Tourmalet</a> thanks to its lightweight/aero properties.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Ridley reckons that the Falcn RS’s combination of low weight, aerodynamics and wider tyre clearances would make it a great option for the <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/tags/classics\" target=\"_blank\">Spring Classics</a>.</p>\n\n\n\n<h2>New frame geometry</h2>\n\n\n\n<table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n\t<th> </th><th>Stack</th><th>Reach</th><th>Fork angle</th><th>Chainstay</th><th>BB drop</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n\t<td>Falcn RS</td><td>551</td><td>397</td><td>73.5</td><td>407</td><td>70</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n\t<td>Helium SLX</td><td>573</td><td>390</td><td>73.5</td><td>405</td><td>66</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n\t<td>Noah Fast Disc</td><td>565</td><td>393</td><td>73.5</td><td>405</td><td>66</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n\n\n\n<p>Ridley has tweaked its <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/road-bike-geometry-handling\" target=\"_blank\">geometry </a>from the Noah Fast and the Helium SLX, with a slightly longer reach and a shorter head tube, which reduces the stack, making for a more aggressive, <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/how-to-win-against-the-wind\" target=\"_blank\">more aero</a> ride position. It’s also increased the bottom bracket drop and the chainstay length to account for the increased diameter of wheels with wider tyres.</p>\n\n\n\n<h2>Ridley Falcn RS specs and prices</h2>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"970\" height=\"647\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/FalcnRS_Packshots-CopyrightRidley-15-970x647.jpg\" alt srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/FalcnRS_Packshots-CopyrightRidley-15-970x646.jpg 970w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/FalcnRS_Packshots-CopyrightRidley-15-300x200.jpg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/FalcnRS_Packshots-CopyrightRidley-15-768x512.jpg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/FalcnRS_Packshots-CopyrightRidley-15-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/FalcnRS_Packshots-CopyrightRidley-15-2048x1366.jpg 2048w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/FalcnRS_Packshots-CopyrightRidley-15-750x500.jpg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/FalcnRS_Packshots-CopyrightRidley-15-1140x760.jpg 1140w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/FalcnRS_Packshots-CopyrightRidley-15-465x310.jpg 465w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/FalcnRS_Packshots-CopyrightRidley-15-620x413.jpg 620w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/FalcnRS_Packshots-CopyrightRidley-15-350x233.jpg 350w\" /><figcaption>Ridley </figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>The new bike is compatible only with electronic shifting and can be set up either 1× or 2×, with a removable front derailleur hanger. There’s hidden brake hose routing through the Forza Cirrus Pro cockpit, which has a 75mm reach and 130m drop. It’s available in four stem length/bar width combinations: 90/380, 100/400, 110/400 and 120/420mm.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>The rear derailleur hanger uses the Universal Derailleur Hanger spec, which looks to be gaining traction outside mountain bikes, where it is commonly used. The latest Santa Cruz Stigmata, for example, has a UDH interface.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Standard specs at launch are SRAM Force AXS or Shimano Ultegra or 105 Di2. You can choose to upspec your drivetrain, as well as wheels and other components via Ridley’s online bike configurator, and also choose your preferred colour. </p>\n\n\n\n<p>The Falcn RS is offered in six sizes from XXS to XL as a complete bike and frameset only.</p>\n\n\n\n<h3>Ridley Falcn RS SRAM Force AXS</h3>\n\n\n\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n\t<td>Frame</td><td>Falcn RS</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n\t<td>Fork</td><td>Falcn RS</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n\t<td>Groupset</td><td>SRAM Force AXS</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n\t<td>Gear ratios</td><td>48/35, 10-33</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n\t<td>Wheels</td><td>DT Swiss ARC1400 50mm</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n\t<td>Tyres</td><td>Vittoria Corsa Pro 28mm</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n\t<td>Brakes</td><td>SRAM Force AXS</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n\t<td>Bar/stem</td><td>Forza Cirrus Pro</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n\t<td>Saddle</td><td>Selle Italia SLR Boost</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n\t<td>Seatpost</td><td>Forza aero 6mm offset</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n\t<td>Sizes</td><td>XXS, XS, S, M, L, XL</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n\t<td>Price</td><td>£8,599 / $12,399 / €9,399</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n\n\n\n<h3>Ridley Falcn RS Shimano Ultegra Di2</h3>\n\n\n\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n\t<td>Frame</td><td>Falcn RS</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n\t<td>Fork</td><td>Falcn RS</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n\t<td>Groupset</td><td>Shimano Ultegra Di2</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n\t<td>Gear ratios</td><td>52/36, 11-30</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n\t<td>Wheels</td><td>DT Swiss ARC1400 50mm</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n\t<td>Tyres</td><td>Vittoria Corsa Pro 28mm</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n\t<td>Brakes</td><td>Shimano Ultegra Di2</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n\t<td>Bar/stem</td><td>Forza Cirrus Pro</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n\t<td>Saddle</td><td>Selle Italia SLR Boost</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n\t<td>Seatpost</td><td>Forza aero 6mm offset</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n\t<td>Sizes</td><td>XXS, XS, S, M, L, XL</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n\t<td>Price</td><td>£8,599 / $12,399 / €9,399</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n\n\n\n<h3>Ridley Falcn RS Shimano 105 Di2</h3>\n\n\n\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n\t<td>Frame</td><td>Falcn RS</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n\t<td>Fork</td><td>Falcn RS</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n\t<td>Groupset</td><td>Shimano 105 Di2</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n\t<td>Gear ratios</td><td>50/34, 11-34</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n\t<td>Wheels</td><td>Forza Levanto DB</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n\t<td>Tyres</td><td>Vittoria Corsa Pro 28mm</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n\t<td>Brakes</td><td>Shimano 105 Di2</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n\t<td>Bar/stem</td><td>Forza Cirrus Pro</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n\t<td>Saddle</td><td>Selle Italia Model Y</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n\t<td>Seatpost</td><td>Forza aero 6mm offset</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n\t<td>Sizes</td><td>XXS, XS, S, M, L, XL</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n\t<td>Price</td><td>£6,799 / $8,249 / €7,399</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n\n\n\n<p></p>\n\n\n\n<p><em>Check out our buyer’s guide to the <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/buying-guides/best-aero-bikes\" target=\"_blank\">best aero road bikes</a> for more fast lightweight options</em>.</p>\n<p>The post <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/news/ridley-falcn-rs\">Ridley Falcn RS merges aero and lightweight to take on Tarmac SL8</a> appeared first on <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk\">Cyclist</a>.</p>","author":"pnorman","siteTitle":"Cyclist.co.uk","siteHash":"561486e7070fa5351de9318ad0fa26c2a39332acba5fc7c7d1694a01d53d431e","entryHash":"503fa7091265f035840938007749e37b4901222578c3aeba4f6ba9e52a99b41d","category":"Cycling"}